statements about colorectal cancer is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dietary influence over the disease is minimal","It is the tenth most common cancer worldwide","Most arise from adenomas or serrated polyps","The incidence rates of the disease are steadily decreasing","South Asia has the highest global incidence of the disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EColorectal is the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird most common\u003C/strong\u003E cancer on a global basis, after breast and lung cancer.  Australia and New Zealand have among the highest age-standardised incidence rates worldwide, closely followed by Southern Europe. The incidence in \u003Cstrong\u003ESouth Asia \u003C/strong\u003Eis perhaps one of the lowest on a global scale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost colorectal cancers arise from adenomas or serrated polyps\u003C/strong\u003E. This reflects the adenoma-carcinoma sequence, which is the primary pathway for colorectal cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor reasons that are not completely clear the \u003Cstrong\u003Eglobal colorectal cancer incidence rates \u003C/strong\u003Eare steadily increasing\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E The incidence rates are increasing in many regions, particularly among younger adults. It is likely that \u003Cstrong\u003Edietary \u003C/strong\u003Efactors are important in this increasing prevalence of the disease, with factors such as high red meat consumption and low fibre intake increasing risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colorectal cancer is the third most common cancer worldwide and incidence is increasing globally, particularly in younger adults","Most colorectal cancers develop from precursor lesions including adenomas and serrated polyps","Australia and New Zealand have among the highest colorectal cancer incidence rates globally"],"references":["Feletto E, Yu XQ, Lew JB, St John DJB, Jenkins MA, Macrae FA, Mahady SE, Canfell K. Trends in Colon and Rectal Cancer Incidence in Australia from 1982 to 2014: Analysis of Data on Over 375,000 Cases. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2019 Jan;28(1):83-90. doi: 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-18-0523. Epub 2018 Dec 7. PMID: 30530848.","Luo Q, Lew JB, Steinberg J, Worthington J, Yu XQ, Caruana M, Soerjomataram I, Bray F, Lawrance S, Arcorace M, O\u0027Connell DL, Canfell K, Feletto E. Trends in colon and rectal cancer mortality in Australia from 1972 to 2015 and associated projections to 2040. Sci Rep. 2022 Mar 7;12(1):3994. doi: 10.1038/s41598-022-07797-x. PMID: 35256697; PMCID: PMC8900106.","Sandler RS. Epidemiology and risk factors for colorectal cancer. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 1996 Dec;25(4):717-35. doi: 10.1016/s0889-8553(05)70271-5. PMID: 8960889.","Rawla P, Sunkara T, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of colorectal cancer: incidence, mortality, survival, and risk factors. Prz Gastroenterol. 2019;14(2):89-103. doi: 10.5114/pg.2018.81072. Epub 2019 Jan 6. PMID: 31616522; PMCID: PMC6791134."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50768"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15220"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50768"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T12:01:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-26T12:01:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7911"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65329"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"